{"id":"1907.01880","submitter":"Olivier Devauchelle","authors":"A. Abramian, O. Devauchelle, G. Seizilles, and E. Lajeunesse","title":"Boltzmann distribution of sediment transport","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett., 123, 1, 014501, 2019","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.123.014501","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn nlin.AO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The coupling of sediment transport with the flow that drives it allows rivers\nto shape their own bed. Cross-stream fluxes of sediment play a crucial, yet\npoorly understood, role in this process. Here, we track particles in a\nlaboratory flume to relate their statistical behavior to the self organization\nof the granular bed they make up. As they travel downstream, the transported\ngrains wander randomly across the bed's surface, thus inducing cross-stream\ndiffusion. The balance of diffusion and gravity results in a peculiar Boltzmann\ndistribution, in which the bed's roughness plays the role of thermal\nfluctuations, while its surface forms the potential well that confines the\nsediment flux.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Jul 2019 12:21:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-04"}
