{"id":"1907.01983","submitter":"Leah B. Shaw","authors":"Sofya Zaytseva, Junping Shi, Leah B Shaw","title":"Model of pattern formation in marsh ecosystems with nonlocal\n  interactions","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.PS q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Smooth cordgrass Spartina alterniflora is a grass species commonly found in\ntidal marshes. It is an ecosystem engineer, capable of modifying the structure\nof its surrounding environment through various feedbacks. The scale-dependent\nfeedback between marsh grass and sediment volume is particularly of interest.\nLocally, the marsh vegetation attenuates hydrodynamic energy, enhancing\nsediment accretion and promoting further vegetation growth. In turn, the\ndiverted water flow promotes the formation of erosion troughs over longer\ndistances. This scale-dependent feedback may explain the characteristic\nspatially varying marsh shoreline, commonly observed in nature. We propose a\nmathematical framework to model grass-sediment dynamics as a system of\nreaction-diffusion equations with an additional nonlocal term quantifying the\nshort-range positive and long-range negative grass-sediment interactions. We\nuse a Mexican-hat kernel function to model this scale-dependent feedback. We\nperform a steady state biharmonic approximation of our system and derive\nconditions for the emergence of spatial patterns, corresponding to a spatially\nvarying marsh shoreline. We find that the emergence of such patterns depends on\nthe spatial scale and strength of the scale-dependent feedback, specified by\nthe width and amplitude of the Mexican-hat kernel function.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Jul 2019 15:13:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-04"}
